# Ownership & Borrowing: A Python Developer's Bridge to Rust

## Starting With What You Know

In Python, you never think about ownership because the garbage collector handles everything:

```python
# Python: Everything is reference-counted + garbage collected
def main():
    a = [1, 2, 3]       # a points to a list on the heap
    b = a                # b points to the SAME list (refcount = 2)
    b.append(4)
    print(a)             # [1, 2, 3, 4] — surprise for beginners!
    # When a and b go out of scope, refcount hits 0 → freed
```

Rust refuses to let two variables own the same data. Here's the mental shift:

```rust
fn main() {
    let a = vec![1, 2, 3];  // a OWNS this Vec on the heap
    let b = a;               // Ownership MOVES to b. a is now invalid.
    // println!("{:?}", a);  // ❌ COMPILE ERROR: value used after move
    println!("{:?}", b);     // ✅ [1, 2, 3]
} // b goes out of scope → memory freed. No GC needed.
```

## The Three Rules (Python Analogies)

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                  RUST'S OWNERSHIP RULES                         │
│                                                                 │
│  1. Every value has exactly ONE owner                           │
│     Python equiv: imagine if assignment always did deepcopy()   │
│     ...but without the performance cost (it's a move)           │
│                                                                 │
│  2. When the owner goes out of scope, the value is dropped      │
│     Python equiv: like a context manager's __exit__, but for    │
│     EVERYTHING, automatically                                   │
│                                                                 │
│  3. You can BORROW references instead of transferring ownership │
│     Python equiv: there is none — Python always shares freely   │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

## Borrowing = "I'm just looking"

Think of borrowing like passing a book to a friend:

```rust
// ---- IMMUTABLE BORROW: "Look but don't touch" ----
fn print_length(data: &Vec<i32>) {   // borrows, doesn't own
    println!("Length: {}", data.len());
}   // data goes out of scope, but nothing is freed (we don't own it)

// ---- MUTABLE BORROW: "You can write in it, but give it back" ----
fn add_element(data: &mut Vec<i32>) {  // exclusive mutable borrow
    data.push(42);
}

fn main() {
    let mut nums = vec![1, 2, 3];

    print_length(&nums);          // immutable borrow — nums still valid
    print_length(&nums);          // can borrow immutably many times

    add_element(&mut nums);       // mutable borrow — exclusive access
    println!("{:?}", nums);       // [1, 2, 3, 42] — we still own it
}
```

The Python equivalent would be:

```python
# Python has no equivalent enforcement, but conceptually:
def print_length(data):       # Is this read-only? Who knows!
    data.append(999)          # Nothing stops you. Bugs happen.
    print(len(data))

nums = [1, 2, 3]
print_length(nums)
print(nums)                   # [1, 2, 3, 999] — unintended mutation
```

## The Borrowing Rules Visualized

```
    ┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
    │         At any given time, you can have:          │
    │                                                   │
    │    EITHER   ∞ immutable borrows (&T)              │
    │                                                   │
    │      OR     1 mutable borrow (&mut T)             │
    │                                                   │
    │              ...but NEVER both.                    │
    └──────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

    Why? This is Rust's compile-time solution to:
    • Data races (threading bugs Python "solves" with the GIL)
    • Iterator invalidation (modifying a list while looping)
    • Use-after-free (not common in Python, but devastating in C)
```

```rust
fn main() {
    let mut data = vec![1, 2, 3];

    let r1 = &data;       // ✅ immutable borrow #1
    let r2 = &data;       // ✅ immutable borrow #2
    println!("{:?} {:?}", r1, r2);

    let r3 = &mut data;   // ✅ mutable borrow (r1, r2 no longer used)
    r3.push(4);

    // let r4 = &data;    // ❌ Can't immutably borrow while r3 is active
}
```

## `String` vs `&str` — The Big Question

This is like Python's relationship between `list` and... well, Python hides this from you.

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                                     │
│   String                          &str                              │
│   ══════                          ════                              │
│   • Owns its data on the heap     • Borrows a view into string data │
│   • Can grow, shrink, mutate      • Read-only, fixed-size window    │
│   • Like Python's str (mutable!)  • Like a memoryview / slice       │
│                                                                     │
│   ┌──────────────┐               ┌──────────┐                      │
│   │ String       │               │ &str     │                      │
│   │ ┌──────────┐ │               │ ptr ─────────┐                  │
│   │ │ ptr ──────────► "Hello, world!"  ◄────────┘                  │
│   │ │ len: 13  │ │               │ len: 5   │                      │
│   │ │ cap: 20  │ │               └──────────┘                      │
│   │ └──────────┘ │               (points to "Hello" portion)       │
│   └──────────────┘                                                  │
│     heap-allocated                 just a pointer + length          │
│                                                                     │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

### The Closest Python Analogy

```python
# Python (conceptual, not real API)
class String:
    """Owned, heap-allocated, growable"""
    def __init__(self):
        self._buffer = bytearray()   # owns the memory

class StrSlice:
    """Borrowed view into someone else's string data"""
    def __init__(self, source, start, end):
        self._view = memoryview(source)[start:end]  # doesn't own anything
```

### In Practice

```rust
fn main() {
    // String: owned, heap-allocated, growable
    let mut owned = String::from("Hello");
    owned.push_str(", world!");        // ✅ can mutate
    println!("{}", owned);             // "Hello, world!"

    // &str: a borrowed slice — a window into string data
    let slice: &str = &owned[0..5];   // borrows "Hello" from owned
    println!("{}", slice);             // "Hello"

    // String literals are &str (baked into the binary)
    let literal: &str = "I live in the binary, not the heap";

    // Why this matters for function signatures:
    greet(slice);                      // ✅ &str works directly
    greet(&owned);                     // ✅ String auto-derefs to &str
    greet(literal);                    // ✅ literals are already &str
}

// Accept &str = "I just need to READ a string, I don't need to own it"
// This is the idiomatic choice for most function parameters
fn greet(name: &str) {
    println!("Hello, {}!", name);
}

// Accept String = "I need to TAKE OWNERSHIP of this string"
fn store_in_database(name: String) {
    // name will be dropped when this function ends
    // unless we move it somewhere (like a struct field)
    println!("Storing: {}", name);
}
```

## Why Rust Makes This Distinction (And Python Doesn't)

```
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                              │
│  Python's approach:                                          │
│  ┌──────────┐     ┌──────────┐     ┌──────────┐            │
│  │ Simplicity│ ──► │ GC + RC  │ ──► │ Runtime  │            │
│  │ for dev   │     │ overhead │     │ cost     │            │
│  └──────────┘     └──────────┘     └──────────┘            │
│                                                              │
│  Rust's approach:                                            │
│  ┌──────────┐     ┌──────────┐     ┌──────────┐            │
│  │ Complexity│ ──► │ Compiler │ ──► │ Zero     │            │
│  │ for dev   │     │ checks   │     │ runtime  │            │
│  └──────────┘     └──────────┘     │ cost     │            │
│                                     └──────────┘            │
│                                                              │
│  The String/&str split exists because Rust needs to know:    │
│  • WHO is responsible for freeing the memory? (String)       │
│  • WHO is just reading it temporarily? (&str)                │
│  • Python never asks because the GC figures it out at        │
│    runtime — at the cost of ~30% overhead and the GIL.       │
│                                                              │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

## Quick Reference: Python → Rust Mental Model

```rust
// Python              →  Rust equivalent
// ──────────────────────────────────────────
// x = [1,2,3]         →  let x = vec![1, 2, 3];      (owned)
// y = x (shared ref)  →  let y = &x;                  (borrow)
// y = x (independent) →  let y = x.clone();           (deep copy)
// y = x (move)        →  let y = x;                   (no Python equiv!)
// def f(x: list)      →  fn f(x: &[i32])              (borrow a slice)
// def f(x: str)       →  fn f(x: &str)                (borrow a string)
// x = "hello"         →  let x: &str = "hello";       (string literal)
// x = str(something)  →  let x: String = something.to_string();
```

## The "Aha!" Moment for Python Devs

```rust
// In Python, this bug is SILENT:
//   items = [1, 2, 3]
//   for item in items:
//       if item == 2:
//           items.remove(item)   # 💥 modifying while iterating

// In Rust, the compiler CATCHES this:
fn main() {
    let mut items = vec![1, 2, 3];

    for item in &items {          // immutable borrow starts
        // items.push(4);         // ❌ COMPILE ERROR: cannot borrow
                                  //    `items` as mutable because it
                                  //    is also borrowed as immutable
    }

    // The borrow checker just prevented a real bug
    // that Python would only catch at runtime (or not at all).
}
```

**The key mindset shift**: In Python, you trust the runtime to manage memory. In Rust, you *prove to the compiler* that your memory access patterns are safe — and in return, you get C-level performance with zero-cost abstractions and no garbage collector.

# Ownership & Borrowing: A Python Developer's Bridge to Rust

## Starting With What You Know

In Python, you never think about ownership because the garbage collector handles everything:

```python
# Python: Everything is reference-counted + garbage collected
def main():
    a = [1, 2, 3]       # a points to a list on the heap
    b = a                # b points to the SAME list (refcount = 2)
    b.append(4)
    print(a)             # [1, 2, 3, 4] — surprise for beginners!
    # When a and b go out of scope, refcount hits 0 → freed
```

Rust refuses to let two variables own the same data. Here's the mental shift:

```rust
fn main() {
    let a = vec![1, 2, 3];  // a OWNS this Vec on the heap
    let b = a;               // Ownership MOVES to b. 'a' is now invalid.
    // println!("{:?}", a);  // ❌ COMPILE ERROR: value used after move
    println!("{:?}", b);     // ✅ [1, 2, 3]
}   // b goes out of scope → memory freed. No GC needed.
```

## The Three Rules (Python Analogies)

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                  RUST'S OWNERSHIP RULES                         │
│                                                                 │
│  1. Each value has exactly ONE owner                            │
│  2. When the owner goes out of scope, the value is dropped      │
│  3. You can BORROW (reference) without taking ownership         │
│                                                                 │
│  Python equivalent mental model:                                │
│  "Imagine if Python had NO garbage collector, variables         │
│   couldn't share objects, and the linter caught every           │
│   use-after-free at write time."                                │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

## Borrowing = "I'm just looking"

Think of borrowing like passing a book to a friend:

```python
# Python: You never think about this — everything is a shared reference
def calculate_length(my_list):
    return len(my_list)  # We're just reading, not taking ownership

data = [1, 2, 3]
length = calculate_length(data)
print(data)  # Still works — Python shares references freely
```

```rust
// Rust: You must be EXPLICIT about borrowing
fn calculate_length(my_vec: &Vec<i32>) -> usize {  // & means "borrow"
    my_vec.len()  // We're just reading
    // my_vec is automatically "returned" to the owner when we're done
}

fn main() {
    let data = vec![1, 2, 3];
    let length = calculate_length(&data);  // Lend it out (immutable borrow)
    println!("{:?}", data);                // ✅ Still works — we only lent it
}
```

### Mutable vs Immutable Borrowing

```rust
// IMMUTABLE borrow (&T) — like multiple readers of a shared Google Doc
fn main() {
    let data = vec![1, 2, 3];
    let r1 = &data;   // ✅ reader 1
    let r2 = &data;   // ✅ reader 2
    println!("{:?} {:?}", r1, r2);  // Multiple readers = fine
}

// MUTABLE borrow (&mut T) — like having exclusive edit access
fn add_element(my_vec: &mut Vec<i32>) {
    my_vec.push(4);
}

fn main() {
    let mut data = vec![1, 2, 3];
    let r1 = &data;          // immutable borrow
    // add_element(&mut data); // ❌ Can't mutably borrow while immutably borrowed!
    println!("{:?}", r1);     // r1's last use
    add_element(&mut data);   // ✅ Now it's fine — r1 is no longer in use
    println!("{:?}", data);   // [1, 2, 3, 4]
}
```

```
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│           THE BORROWING RULE (memorize this)             │
│                                                          │
│   At any given time, you can have EITHER:                │
│     • ANY number of immutable references (&T)            │
│     OR                                                   │
│     • Exactly ONE mutable reference (&mut T)             │
│                                                          │
│   Never both. This prevents data races at COMPILE TIME.  │
│                                                          │
│   Python analogy: imagine if Python enforced that you    │
│   can't iterate over a list while another thread         │
│   modifies it — but checked at write time, not runtime.  │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

## The Big Question: `String` vs `&str`

This is where Python developers get most confused. Let's build up to it:

```python
# In Python, there's just ONE string type:
name = "hello"          # str
name2 = "hello" + "!"   # str — same type, Python handles everything

# You never think about:
#   - Is this string on the stack or heap?
#   - Who owns this string's memory?
#   - Is this a view into another string or a copy?
```

Rust makes you think about ALL of that:

```rust
fn main() {
    // String → OWNED, heap-allocated, growable
    // Python analogy: like a Python list — you own it, you can mutate it
    let mut owned = String::from("hello");
    owned.push_str(" world");  // ✅ Can modify — we own it
    owned.push('!');           // ✅ Can grow

    // &str → BORROWED slice, a "view" into string data
    // Python analogy: like a memoryview or a numpy slice — 
    //   it points to data owned by someone else
    let slice: &str = &owned[0..5];   // "hello" — a window into 'owned'
    let literal: &str = "hello";       // Points to data baked into the binary

    println!("{}", slice);   // "hello"
    println!("{}", literal); // "hello"
}
```

### Visualizing the Memory Layout

```
    Stack                          Heap
    ┌──────────────┐              ┌───┬───┬───┬───┬───┬───┬───┬───┬───┬───┬───┬──┐
    │ owned:       │              │ h │ e │ l │ l │ o │   │ w │ o │ r │ l │ d │! │
    │  ptr ────────┼─────────────►│   │   │   │   │   │   │   │   │   │   │   │  │
    │  len: 12     │              └───┴───┴───┴───┴───┴───┴───┴───┴───┴───┴───┴──┘
    │  capacity: 12│                ▲
    ├──────────────┤                │
    │ slice:       │                │
    │  ptr ────────┼────────────────┘
    │  len: 5      │              (points to first 5 bytes of owned's data)
    ├──────────────┤
    │ literal:     │              Binary/static memory
    │  ptr ────────┼─────────────►┌───┬───┬───┬───┬───┐
    │  len: 5      │              │ h │ e │ l │ l │ o │
    └──────────────┘              └───┴───┴───┴───┴───┘

    String = (ptr, len, capacity)  →  OWNS the heap data
    &str   = (ptr, len)            →  BORROWS someone else's data
```

### The Closest Python Analogy

```python
# The BEST Python analogy for String vs &str:

import array

# String ≈ bytearray (owned, mutable, growable)
owned = bytearray(b"hello")
owned.extend(b" world")  # Can grow

# &str ≈ memoryview (borrowed view, no copy, can't outlive source)
view = memoryview(owned)[0:5]  # A window into 'owned'

# Or think of it like:
# String ≈ a Python str that you OWN and can rebuild
# &str   ≈ a read-only reference/slice into someone else's string

# The key insight: &str doesn't allocate new memory.
# It's just a pointer + length into existing string data.
```

### Why Does Rust Make This Distinction?

```rust
// REASON 1: Performance — avoid unnecessary copies
// ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
fn greet_bad(name: String) {
    // This TAKES OWNERSHIP — caller can't use their string anymore
    // Or they must .clone() it (heap allocation!)
    println!("Hello, {}!", name);
}

fn greet_good(name: &str) {
    // This BORROWS — zero cost, no allocation, caller keeps their string
    println!("Hello, {}!", name);
}

fn main() {
    let owned = String::from("Alice");
    let literal = "Bob";

    greet_good(&owned);    // ✅ String auto-coerces to &str
    greet_good(literal);   // ✅ &str works directly
    greet_good(&owned[0..3]); // ✅ Slices work too — "Ali"

    // greet_bad needs to CONSUME or clone:
    greet_bad(owned.clone()); // Heap allocation just to say hello!
    greet_bad(owned);         // Moves — can't use 'owned' after this
}
```

```rust
// REASON 2: Clarity of ownership — who frees the memory?
// ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
struct User {
    name: String,    // User OWNS this string — it lives as long as User does
}

fn display_name(name: &str) {  // Just peeking — no ownership responsibility
    println!("{}", name);
}

// REASON 3: Compile-time safety — dangling references are impossible
// ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
fn dangling() -> &str {
    let s = String::from("hello");
    // &s  // ❌ COMPILE ERROR: s is dropped here, reference would dangle
    //       // In C this would be a use-after-free bug
    //       // In Python this never happens (GC keeps it alive)
    //       // In Rust the compiler catches it
    "hello" // ✅ This is fine — string literals live forever ('static)
}
```

## The Practical Cheat Sheet

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    WHEN TO USE WHICH                                │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│                                                                     │
│  Use &str when:                    Use String when:                 │
│  ─────────────                     ───────────────                  │
│  • Function parameters             • Struct fields (you need to     │
│    (accept the widest input)         own the data)                  │
│  • You're just reading             • Building/modifying strings     │
│  • You don't need the data         • Returning a new string from    │
│    to outlive the current scope      a function                     │
│                                    • Data that must live beyond     │
│                                      the current borrow scope       │
│                                                                     │
│  Python analogy:                   Python analogy:                  │
│  "I'm borrowing your book          "I'm buying my own copy          │
│   to read a chapter"                so I can keep it forever"       │
│                                                                     │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  CONVERSION:                                                        │
│    String → &str    cheap:  &my_string  or  my_string.as_str()     │
│    &str → String    costs:  my_str.to_string()  or  String::from() │
│                             (allocates on heap)                     │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

## The "Aha" Moment for Python Developers

```rust
// In Python, the garbage collector is your safety net.
// In Rust, the COMPILER is your safety net.
//
// Python: "I'll figure out when to free memory at runtime"
//   → Simple to write, but: GC pauses, memory overhead, 
//     can't catch data races
//
// Rust: "I'll prove memory safety at compile time"
//   → Harder to write, but: zero runtime cost, no GC,
//     data races are impossible
//
// The ownership system IS the garbage collector —
// it just runs at compile time instead of runtime.
```

The distinction between `String` and `&str` exists because **Rust refuses to hide the cost of memory operations from you**. In Python, `name = other_name` might increment a reference count, copy nothing, or trigger a GC cycle — you never know. In Rust, every allocation, copy, and borrow is visible in the type system. That's the trade-off: more thinking upfront, zero surprises at runtime.

